<main style='min-height:100vh;padding-bottom:20px'><header style='max-width:860px;margin:0 auto;padding:60px 20px 30px;text-align:center'><h1 style='color:#f0ece4;font-size:2.4rem;margin:0 0 14px'>Documentary Discussion Guides</h1><p style='color:#b8b2a6;font-size:1.08rem;line-height:1.65;max-width:660px;margin:0 auto'>Companion guides for each episode of The Mind’s Gambit — written for classrooms, chess clubs, book clubs, and families who want the conversation to continue after the credits.</p></header><section style='max-width:860px;margin:0 auto;padding:0 20px 28px'><div style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:12px;padding:18px 22px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0'><strong style='color:#d4af37'>How to use these guides:</strong> watch the episode first, together if you can. Then pick three or four questions — not all of them — and let the conversation go where it wants. There are no right answers here; the questions are doors, not tests. You do not need to know how to play chess to take part in any of them.</p></div></section><section style='max-width:860px;margin:0 auto;padding:0 20px 30px'><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:14px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:18px 22px'><span style='min-width:44px;height:44px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700;font-size:1.05rem'>1</span><span style='flex:1'><strong style='display:block;color:#f0ece4;font-size:1.1rem'>The Constant</strong><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.9rem'>Attention · ritual · why we return</span></span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open guide</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 24px 24px 24px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px'><strong style='color:#d4af37'>About this episode — </strong>The opening reflection of the series: on chess, attention, and what makes a player return to the board, year after year, loss after loss.</p><p style='color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;margin:0 0 10px'>For discussion</p><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>1.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>The episode is called The Constant. In a life where everything changes, what does chess stay constant FOR — what is it holding steady?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>2.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>When did you last give anything your complete, undivided attention? What did it feel like — and why is that feeling so rare now?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>3.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>People return to chess knowing they will lose half their games. What else in life do we keep returning to despite losing — and what does that say about us?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>4.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>Is the board an escape from the world, or a mirror of it? Can it be both at once?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>5.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>The episode treats a board game with the seriousness usually reserved for art or religion. Is that seriousness deserved — or is it part of the spell?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>6.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>What is YOUR constant — the practice or place you return to when everything else is noise?</p></div><a href='/watch' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:10px'>Watch the episode &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:14px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:18px 22px'><span style='min-width:44px;height:44px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700;font-size:1.05rem'>2</span><span style='flex:1'><strong style='display:block;color:#f0ece4;font-size:1.1rem'>The Number</strong><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.9rem'>Measurement · identity · self-worth</span></span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open guide</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 24px 24px 24px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px'><strong style='color:#d4af37'>About this episode — </strong>On rating, identity, and the strange relationship between a chess player and the number that follows them their whole career.</p><p style='color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;margin:0 0 10px'>For discussion</p><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>1.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>A chess rating follows a player everywhere, rising and falling in public. What numbers follow YOU through life — grades, salaries, followers, steps — and how public are they?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>2.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>When does measuring a person help them grow, and when does the measurement start to replace the person?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>3.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>The episode suggests a player can begin to believe they ARE their rating. Have you ever caught your self-worth tracking a number? What broke the spell — or has it?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>4.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>Who benefits from a world where everyone is constantly ranked? Who pays for it?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>5.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>Imagine chess with no ratings at all — just games. What would be lost? What would be freed?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>6.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>If you could un-attach one number from your life forever, which one — and why that one?</p></div><a href='/watch' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:10px'>Watch the episode &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:14px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:18px 22px'><span style='min-width:44px;height:44px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700;font-size:1.05rem'>3</span><span style='flex:1'><strong style='display:block;color:#f0ece4;font-size:1.1rem'>Brilliance That Bleeds</strong><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.9rem'>Genius · sacrifice · the hidden price</span></span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open guide</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 24px 24px 24px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px'><strong style='color:#d4af37'>About this episode — </strong>Portraits of players whose greatness extracted a price the public never sees — where chess brilliance and personal cost intersect.</p><p style='color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;margin:0 0 10px'>For discussion</p><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>1.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>The title says brilliance BLEEDS. What is the price the public never sees — in chess, in sport, in music, in any field of excellence?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>2.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>We often tell young people that greatness requires sacrifice. Is that a truth — or a story institutions tell to excuse what they ask of people?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>3.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>Where exactly is the line between dedication and harm? Who in a young player’s life is responsible for watching that line?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>4.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>Why are we, the audience, so drawn to the figure of the suffering genius? What does our fascination feed?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>5.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>Can a person love the thing that is hurting them? What would it mean to love it differently?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>6.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>If a brilliant child is being consumed by their gift, who has the duty to intervene — the family, the coach, the federation, the child? What usually happens instead?</p></div><a href='/watch' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:10px'>Watch the episode &rarr;</a></div></details><details style='background:rgba(255,255,255,.04);border:1px solid rgba(255,255,255,.09);border-radius:14px;margin-bottom:14px;overflow:hidden'><summary style='list-style:none;cursor:pointer;display:flex;align-items:center;gap:16px;padding:18px 22px'><span style='min-width:44px;height:44px;border-radius:50%;background:rgba(212,175,55,.13);color:#d4af37;display:flex;align-items:center;justify-content:center;font-weight:700;font-size:1.05rem'>4</span><span style='flex:1'><strong style='display:block;color:#f0ece4;font-size:1.1rem'>The Queen’s Burden</strong><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.9rem'>Women in chess · institutions · the longer game</span></span><span style='color:#8a8478;font-size:.85rem;white-space:nowrap'>Open guide</span></summary><div style='padding:4px 24px 24px 24px'><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.7;margin:0 0 16px'><strong style='color:#d4af37'>About this episode — </strong>On women in chess — the talent, the institutional walls, and what a queen’s move means inside and outside the 64 squares.</p><p style='color:#f0ece4;font-weight:600;margin:0 0 10px'>For discussion</p><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>1.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>The strongest piece on the board is the queen — yet the game around the board has rarely been kind to women. How do you explain that contradiction?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>2.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>Which barriers in the episode struck you as institutional — written into the rules and structures — and which as cultural, living in attitudes and rooms?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>3.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>What changes in a chess club, visibly and invisibly, when a girl walks in? What would have to be true for nothing to change at all?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>4.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>The title speaks of a burden. What extra weight does a woman carry to the same board, beyond the game itself?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>5.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>What does a queen’s move mean OUTSIDE the 64 squares — in the lives of the women the episode follows?</p></div><div style='display:flex;gap:14px;align-items:flex-start;border-left:2px solid rgba(212,175,55,.4);padding:6px 0 6px 16px;margin-bottom:10px'><span style='color:#d4af37;font-weight:700'>6.</span><p style='color:#c9c3b6;line-height:1.6;margin:0'>What would real equality in chess actually look like — separate titles, mixed fields, different rooms? What would convince you it had arrived?</p></div><a href='/watch' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:10px 22px;border-radius:9px;text-decoration:none;margin-top:10px'>Watch the episode &rarr;</a></div></details></section><section style='max-width:860px;margin:0 auto;padding:6px 20px 70px'><div style='background:linear-gradient(135deg,rgba(212,175,55,.13),rgba(212,175,55,.04));border:1px solid rgba(212,175,55,.35);border-radius:16px;padding:28px;text-align:center'><h2 style='color:#d4af37;margin:0 0 10px;font-size:1.35rem'>Bring the series to your group</h2><p style='color:#b8b2a6;margin:0 auto 18px;max-width:560px;line-height:1.6'>Teaching with the series, or running a club screening? We would love to hear how the conversations went.</p><a href='/watch' style='display:inline-block;background:#d4af37;color:#0f1117;font-weight:700;padding:12px 26px;border-radius:10px;text-decoration:none;margin:4px'>Watch the Series</a><a href='/#contact' style='display:inline-block;border:1px solid #d4af37;color:#d4af37;font-weight:700;padding:12px 26px;border-radius:10px;text-decoration:none;margin:4px'>Contact Us</a></div></section></main>
<style>section[data-reveal]{transition:transform 0.3s ease;overflow:hidden;}section[data-reveal]:hover{transform:scale(1.02);}#about,#book,#blog,#chess-school-home{padding-top:10px !important;scroll-margin-top:80px;}
